        output='## Related-Party Relationships and Pre-Merger Intercompany Activity Following the xAI and X Holdings Mergers\n\n### 1. Where the Filing Discusses Pre-Merger Intercompany Activity\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 addresses pre-merger intercompany activity in three principal locations:\n\n**A. Note 1 — Nature of Business (Common-Control Accounting)**\n\nThe filing states that the Mergers were accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control because Mr. Musk held a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X through his majority voting interest in each entity. Critically, Note 1 provides:\n\n> "The Company\'s consolidated financial statements have been prepared to reflect the retrospective combination of the net assets of the entities at their historical carrying amounts for all periods presented. No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded and **all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation**."\n\nThis means that pre-merger transactions *among SpaceX, xAI, and X themselves* are **not** separately disclosed as related-party transactions in the consolidated financial statements — they are eliminated. What remains disclosed are transactions with **external** related parties (Tesla, The Boring Company, Valor, Musk-affiliated entities) that persist post-merger.\n\n**B. Prospectus Preamble (Retrospective Recasting)**\n\n> "The consolidated financial statements of SpaceX have been retrospectively recast for all periods presented to include (i) the historical results of X.AI Holdings Corp., which was acquired by SpaceX, effective February 2, 2026 (the \'xAI Merger\'), and X Holdings Corp. (\'X Holdings\'), which was acquired by xAI, effective March 28, 2025 (the \'X Merger\'), because these transactions were between entities under common control..."\n\nThe preamble also notes this presentation "constitutes a change in reporting entity."\n\n**C. "Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions" Section (Item 404 of Regulation S-K)**\n\nThis section explicitly extends to pre-merger activity:\n\n> "On February 2, 2026, we effected the xAI Merger, pursuant to which we acquired xAI (which includes X). For the purposes of the disclosures set forth in this section pursuant to Item 404 of Regulation S-K, the transactions described below also include certain agreements and transactions originally entered into by xAI or X Holdings prior to the xAI Merger to the extent that such agreements and transactions are ongoing following the consummation of [the xAI Merger]."\n\nIt establishes a three-part threshold for disclosure: (1) the company is a participant; (2) the amount exceeds $120,000; and (3) a director, executive officer, 5%+ holder, or their immediate family member has a direct or indirect material interest.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Related-Party Relationships Within the Consolidated Structure\n\n**A. Internal Corporate Structure (Post-Merger)**\n\n| Entity | Relationship | Acquisition Date |\n|---|---|---|\n| SpaceX (parent) | Reporting company | — |\n| xAI (X.AI Holdings Corp.) | Wholly-owned subsidiary of SpaceX | February 2, 2026 ("xAI Merger Date") |\n| X Holdings Corp. ("X") | Wholly-owned subsidiary of xAI | March 28, 2025 ("X Merger") |\n| X.AI Corp. | Wholly-owned subsidiary of xAI | March 28, 2025 |\n| Falcon Landing, LLC | SpaceX subsidiary operating aircraft | — |\n| CTC | Subsidiary of xAI / indirect subsidiary of SpaceX | — |\n\nAll historical intercompany transactions among these entities have been eliminated in consolidation.\n\n**B. External Related-Party Transactions (Ongoing Post-Merger)**\n\nThe filing discloses ongoing related-party transactions with the following counterparties:\n\n1. **Tesla, Inc.** — Mr. Musk serves as CEO and director of Tesla and holds ~20% of Tesla stock. Tesla, in turn, holds 18,990,195 shares of SpaceX Class A common stock (<1.0% post-offering). Disclosed transactions include:\n   - SpaceX commercial, licensing, and support agreements with Tesla ($11M in 2023; $4M in 2024; $144M in 2025; $0.2M Jan–Feb 2026)\n   - xAI commercial, licensing, and support agreements with Tesla ($191M in 2024; $506M in 2025; $34M Jan–Feb 2026)\n   - X Holdings advertising agreements (Tesla purchasing ads on X)\n   - Aircraft usage (SpaceX invoicing Tesla since April 2016)\n   - Capital equipment purchases from Tesla (Megapacks: $506M in 2025, $191M in 2024; Cybertrucks: $131M at MSRP in 2025)\n   - Tesla\'s January 2026 agreement to invest $2,000M in xAI Series E Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock, which converted post-merger into the right to acquire SpaceX Class A common stock; SpaceX issued 3.8M shares to Tesla on March 12, 2026\n\n2. **The Boring Company** — Office lease (X entered into an office space lease with a Boring Company subsidiary in 2024); tunnel construction by The Boring Company in Bastrop, Texas ($1M in 2025)\n\n3. **Musk Industries LLC** — Real property lease to xAI ($0.5M in 2024; $2M in 2025; $0.2M Jan–Feb 2026)\n\n4. **Security Company (Musk-owned)** — Services agreement for security services concerning Mr. Musk ($2M in 2023; $3M in 2024; $4M in 2025; $1M Jan–Feb 2026)\n\n5. **Antonio J. Gracias / Valor Equity Partners** — Mr. Gracias serves on SpaceX\'s board and is the founder, CEO, and Chief Investment Officer of Valor Equity Partners. Disclosed transactions include:\n   - Three equipment lease agreements between a subsidiary of xAI (CTC) and Valor for computing and related equipment, with aggregate cash payments of approximately $20,206 million over the life of the leases ($6,986M + $6,633M + $6,587M)\n   - SpaceX (or one of its subsidiaries) guarantees the lessees\' payment and performance obligations\n   - Payments made: $885M in 2025; $857M from January 1–February 28, 2026\n   - The Valor transaction was deemed a **failed sale-leaseback**, resulting in debt of approximately $4,507 million as of December 31, 2025, and interest expense of $66 million for the year ended December 31, 2025\n   - X received payments from Valor for API services ($1M in 2024; $1M in 2025; $0.1M Jan–Feb 2026)\n\n6. **Elon Musk Stock Purchases** — In 2025, Mr. Musk, through his trust, purchased $1,421 million of common stock from current and former shareholders\n\n7. **xAI Merger Consideration** — On February 2, 2026, SpaceX issued to xAI stockholders 321.7 million shares of Class A Common Stock, 121.7 million shares of Class B Common Stock (pre-2026 Stock Split basis), and $2,947 million in cash\n\n8. **Share Repurchases from Related Parties** — Various repurchases from eligible employees and existing shareholders, including Q1 2026 repurchases of 25.4M SpaceX common shares for $2,413M from eligible current/former xAI employees (xAI Merger-related)\n\n9. **Falcon Landing, LLC** — SpaceX owns and operates, through this subsidiary, three aircraft for use by directors, executive officers, and other personnel\n\n---\n\n### 3. Key Analytical Takeaways\n\n- **Intra-group pre-merger activity is eliminated, not disclosed**: Because the Mergers were accounted for as common-control reorganizations, all historical related-party transactions *among SpaceX, xAI, and X* have been eliminated in consolidation. The filing does not separately quantify these pre-merger intercompany flows.\n\n- **External related-party transactions are aggregated by counterparty**: The "Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions" section presents ongoing transactions by counterparty (Tesla, Boring Company, Valor, Musk-affiliated entities), with the understanding that some originated at the xAI or X level before consolidation.\n\n- **The disclosure architecture distinguishes between**: (i) eliminated intra-group transactions (Note 1); (ii) retrospectively recast historical financials (Prospectus preamble); and (iii) ongoing external related-party transactions that continue post-merger (Item 404 section).\n\n- **Material ongoing exposure**: The Valor equipment leases (~$20.2 billion aggregate) and the failed sale-leaseback accounting treatment (~$4.5 billion debt) represent the most financially significant ongoing related-party relationship, with SpaceX guaranteeing the lessees\' obligations.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Key Disclosure Locations\n\n| Topic | Location in Filing |\n|---|---|\n| Common control accounting & elimination of intercompany transactions | Note 1 (Nature of Business) |\n| Retrospective recasting of financial statements | Prospectus preamble; Note 1 |\n| Pre-merger agreements ongoing post-merger | "Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions" section |\n| Tesla commercial/advertising/aircraft transactions | "Transactions with Elon Musk and Affiliated Entities" |\n| Boring Company, Musk Industries, security company | Same section, subsequent paragraphs |\n| Valor equipment leases and failed sale-leaseback | "Relationship with Antonio J. Gracias and Affiliated Entities"; Note 10 (Debt) cross-reference |\n| xAI Merger consideration | Note 13 (Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock and Shareholders\' Equity) |\n| Tesla xAI investment conversion | Separate subsection within related party disclosures |\n| Share repurchase activity | Capital stock roll-forward tables; Notes 12/13 |\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Note 1 (Nature of Business), Prospectus Preamble, and \'Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions\' section"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
        error=None,
